urned%20as%20needed%20by%20most%20living%20cells%2C%20for%20growth%2C%20health%2C%20and%20reproduction.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAlmost%20every%20living%20thing%20on%20the%20planet%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmilnepublishing.geneseo.edu%2Fbotany%2Fchapter%2Fmatter-energy-and-organisms%2F%5C%22%3Etakes%20its%20energy%20from%20this%20sun-fed%20system%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20either%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FTrophic_level%5C%22%3Etapping%20into%20it%3C%2Fa%3E%20closer%20to%20the%20source%2C%20like%20the%20plants%20who%20first%20capture%20it%2C%20then%20the%20deer%20who%20eat%20the%20plants%2C%20or%20further%20from%20the%20source%2C%20like%20the%20big%20cats%20who%20eat%20the%20deer%2C%20or%20the%20fungi%20and%20microbes%20who%20eat%20all%20of%20these%20after%20they%E2%80%99ve%20lived%20and%20died.%20Humans%20eat%20all%20of%20these%20things%20too.%20After%20we%20die%2C%20we%E2%80%99re%20also%20eaten%20by%20the%20fungi%20and%20microbes%3B%20the%20materials%20that%20make%20up%20our%20bodies%20are%20returned%20into%20the%20soil%20and%20the%20air%2C%20and%20eventually%20reabsorbed%20by%20the%20plants.%20Energy%20and%20materials%20flow%20through%20this%20circle%20of%20life%E2%80%94really%2C%20multiple%20interconnected%20circles%2C%20or%20a%20%3Cem%3Eweb%3C%2Fem%3E%20of%20life%E2%80%94with%20each%20species%20occupying%20its%20place%2C%20or%20%3Cem%3Eniche%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20within%20the%20flow.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20380px)%2085vw%2C%20380px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25112948%2FEnergy-1.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22380%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25112948%2FEnergy-1.jpg%20883w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25112948%2FEnergy-1-221x300.jpg%20221w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25112948%2FEnergy-1-753x1024.jpg%20753w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-698745%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22516%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EA%20diagram%20showing%20how%20energy%20flows%20through%20an%20ecosystem.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELike%20every%20other%20being%20on%20Earth%2C%20humans%20once%20lived%20within%20the%20constraints%20of%20our%20energy%20niche%3Cem%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%20That%20is%20to%20say%2C%20we%20lived%20directly%20upon%20what%20our%20environment%20could%20immediately%20provide%2C%20existing%20in%20a%20kind%20of%20balance%20with%20whatever%20landscape%20we%20called%20home.%20The%20materials%20we%20consumed%20were%20returned%20to%20the%20land%20at%20roughly%20the%20same%20rate%20that%20we%20took%20them%20in%2C%20through%20the%20waste%20we%20produced%2C%20including%20our%20excrement%20and%20the%20bodies%20of%20our%20dead.%20If%20we%20produced%20waste%20too%20rapidly%20for%20the%20local%20ecosystem%20to%20readily%20reabsorb%20it%2C%20that%20waste%20became%20pollution%2C%20throwing%20us%20out%20of%20balance%2C%20degrading%20our%20home%20ecosystem%20and%20thus%20diminishing%20its%20productive%20capacity.%20If%20we%20consumed%20resources%20faster%20than%20the%20Earth%20could%20replenish%20them%2C%20again%20out%20of%20balance%2C%20the%20landscape%20became%20overdrawn%2C%20exhausted%2C%20degraded.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EGenetic%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC378623%2F%5C%22%3Eevidence%20suggests%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20the%20ancestors%20of%20the%20peoples%20living%20on%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdigitalcommons.wayne.edu%2Fcgi%2Fviewcontent.cgi%3Farticle%3D2055%26context%3Dhumbiol%5C%22%3EAndaman%20Islands%3C%2Fa%3E%20first%20landed%20there%20at%20least%2025%2C000%20years%20ago%E2%80%94%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.egyankosh.ac.in%2Fbitstream%2F123456789%2F69339%2F1%2FUnit-3.pdf%5C%22%3Eand%20likely%20closer%20to%2060%2C000%3C%2Fa%3E%20years%20ago.%20For%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20years%20they%20successfully%20lived%20in%20sustainable%20balance%20with%20their%20island%20ecosystems%3A%20dots%20of%20land%20with%20clearly%20constrained%20limits%20to%20growth.%20The%20ongoing%20destruction%20of%20their%20cultures%2C%20due%20to%20colonisation%20by%20the%20British%20and%20then%20mainland%20Indians%2C%20undoubtedly%20represents%20the%20loss%20of%20a%20valuable%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.scientificamerican.com%2Farticle%2Fthis-ancient-language-has-the-only-grammar-based-entirely-on-the-human-body%2F%5C%22%3Eknowledge%20system%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20how%20to%20live%20on%20Earth.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20at%20a%20balanced%20rate%20of%20consumption%20and%20waste%2C%20our%20population%20could%20grow%20to%20fill%20the%20carrying%20capacity%20of%20the%20land%E2%80%94that%20is%2C%20the%20number%20of%20humans%20the%20local%20ecosystem%20could%20sustainably%20support%20in%20a%20given%20way%20of%20life%E2%80%94and%20there%20it%20had%20to%20stabilise.%20If%20we%20spoiled%20the%20landscape%20by%20over-extracting%20resources%2C%20over-polluting%2C%20or%20otherwise%20carelessly%20destroying%20the%20integrity%20of%20the%20ecosystem%2C%20we%20would%20overshoot%20the%20land%E2%80%99s%20carrying%20capacity%2C%20impoverishing%20ourselves%20in%20the%20same%20moment.%20The%20feedback%20from%20the%20local%20ecosystem%20in%20response%20to%20such%20%3Cem%3Eecological%20overshoot%3C%2Fem%3E%20could%20be%20quick%20and%20stern%2C%20as%20resources%20then%20declined%20in%20the%20following%20season%20or%20year%2C%20causing%20hunger%20and%20other%20problems.%20Societies%20that%20resisted%20adjusting%20their%20ways%20to%20accommodate%20the%20needs%20of%20the%20ecosystem%2C%20who%20instead%20forced%20their%20environment%20to%20bend%20to%20their%20own%20priorities%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2F3quarksdaily.com%2F3quarksdaily%2F2022%2F02%2Fstories-of-collapse.html%5C%22%3Ewould%20collapse%3C%2Fa%3E.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2F3quarksdaily.com%2F3quarksdaily%2F2022%2F01%2Fstories-of-continuity.html%5C%22%3ESuccessful%20communities%20learned%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20their%20costly%20mistakes%20and%20adjusted%20their%20lifestyles%20accordingly.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThere%20could%20be%20no%20hoarding%20of%20surpluses%2C%20no%20wanton%20annihilation%20or%20dismemberment%20of%20the%20local%20ecosystem%20in%20this%20kind%20of%20%3Cem%3Eimmediate-return%20economy%3C%2Fem%3E%2C%20as%20typified%20by%20nomadic%20foraging%20cultures.%20Living%20within%20the%20constraints%20of%20the%20land%20doesn%E2%80%99t%20easily%20allow%20for%20the%20kinds%20of%20socioeconomic%20differentiation%20we%20know%20today.%20Without%20surpluses%20or%20hoarding%2C%20there%20could%20be%20no%20rich%20or%20poor%20people%2C%20no%20persistent%20economic%20stratifications%20or%20classes%20of%20people.%20And%20since%20most%20individuals%20were%20reasonably%20adept%20in%20the%20necessary%20skills%20of%20provision%20and%20survival%2C%20there%20was%20little%20leverage%20for%20tyranny%20or%20coercion.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2062vw%2C%20840px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113719%2Find-jar-tf-284_gallery_large.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22910%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113719%2Find-jar-tf-284_gallery_large.jpg%20910w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113719%2Find-jar-tf-284_gallery_large-300x198.jpg%20300w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-698749%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22600%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EThe%20Jarawa%20people%20of%20the%20Andaman%20Islands%20lived%20in%20balance%20with%20their%20island%20environment%20for%20tens%20of%20thousands%20of%20years.%20Photo%3A%20Survival%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EOf%20course%2C%20every%20community%20has%20selfish%20individuals%20who%20nevertheless%20seek%20to%20over-exploit%20resources%20or%20to%20control%20other%20members%20of%20their%20group.%20There%20are%20always%20those%20who%20remain%20heedless%20of%20the%20consequences%20to%20others%20when%20they%20upset%20the%20ecological%20balance%20or%20community%20life%2C%20so%20long%20as%20they%20find%20some%20personal%20advantage%20in%20doing%20so.%20Such%20greedy%20or%20antisocial%20members%20of%20any%20group%20have%20probably%20always%20gotten%20away%20with%20some%20amount%20of%20bad%20behaviour.%20But%20excessively%20exploitative%2C%20damaging%2C%20or%20tyrannical%20social%20campaigns%20could%20not%20have%20persisted%20for%20long%20among%20nomadic%20foraging%20peoples%2C%20certainly%20not%20enough%20to%20define%20a%20way%20of%20life%20for%20an%20entire%20community.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAmong%20nomadic%20foraging%20groups%20there%20is%20enormous%20social%20and%20cultural%20resistance%20to%20greed%20or%20wilful%20attempts%20to%20concentrate%20social%20power.%20This%20plays%20out%20in%20what%20are%20called%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.unl.edu%2Frhames%2Fcourses%2Fcurrent%2Freadings%2Fboehm.pdf%5C%22%3Ereverse%20dominance%20hierarchies%3C%2Fa%3E.%20That%20is%2C%20anyone%20who%20aggressively%20attempts%20to%20promote%20themselves%2C%20control%20others%2C%20hoard%20resources%2C%20or%20force%20actions%20seen%20by%20others%20as%20unfairly%20self-serving%20will%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.filmsforaction.org%2Fnews%2Fhow-huntergatherers-maintained-their-egalitarian-ways-three-complementary-theories%2F%5C%22%3Eactively%20be%20pulled%20down%3C%2Fa%3E%20by%20their%20community%2C%20through%20humiliation%20or%20violence%E2%80%94sometimes%20even%20to%20the%20point%20where%20the%20unhappy%20group%20murders%20the%20aspiring%20tyrant.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20Indian%20subcontinent%20saw%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Findia.mongabay.com%2F2021%2F02%2Fbeasts-that-once-roamed-the-indian-subcontinent-could-hold-clues-to-evolution-and-extinction%2F%5C%22%3Erelatively%20few%20megafaunal%20losses%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20the%20global%20Late%20Quaternary%20extinction%20event%2C%20between%2050%2C000%E2%80%9310%2C000%20years%20ago.%20Losses%20included%20two%20elephant%20species%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FPalaeoloxodon-namadicus%5C%22%3EPalaeoloxodon%3C%2Fa%3E%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FStegodon%5C%22%3EStegodon%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20a%20hippopotamus%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fprehistoric-fauna.com%2FHexaprotodon%5C%22%3EHexaprotodon%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FEquus_namadicus%5C%22%3Ezebra-like%20equine%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20and%20ostriches%20(still%20found%20in%20Africa).%20However%2C%20in%20today%E2%80%99s%20age%20of%20radical%20deforestation%20and%20industrialisation%2C%20just%20within%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fjeevoka.com%2F6-charismatic-extinct-indian-animals-in-the-last-300-years-due-to-anthropogenic-reasons%2Fs%5C%22%3Elast%20300%20years%3C%2Fa%3E%20India%20has%20already%20lost%20its%20aurochs%2C%20two%20types%20of%20rhinoceros%2C%20cheetahs%2C%20and%20civet%20cats%2C%20plus%20several%20bird%20species.%20At%20least%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.indiaspend.com%2Fearthcheck%2Fbiodiversity-collapse-whats-foiling-indias-conservation-efforts-820777%5C%22%3E97%20more%20Indian%20species%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20presently%20on%20the%20verge%2C%20including%20its%20last%20elephants%2C%20lions%2C%20dolphins%2C%20and%20tigers.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EA%20narcissist%20may%20also%20be%20levelled%20by%20the%20dissolution%20of%20their%20group%20through%20attrition%3A%20people%20just%20leave%20the%20braggart%E2%80%99s%20company%E2%80%94%E2%80%98vote%20with%20their%20feet%2C%E2%80%99%20as%20anthropologists%20like%20to%20say.%20Or%20they%20may%20expel%20that%20individual.%20This%20was%20possible%20because%20there%20was%20almost%20unlimited%20freedom%20of%20movement%20among%20people%20in%20nomadic%20foraging%20societies%3A%20individuals%20were%20free%20to%20walk%20away%3B%20their%20broadly%20seeded%20networks%20of%20kinship%20and%20reciprocity%20assured%20they%20had%20somewhere%20else%20to%20go%2C%20whether%20to%20join%20another%20group%20just%20across%20the%20valley%20or%20hundreds%20of%20miles%20away.%20This%20isn%E2%80%99t%20to%20suggest%20that%20no%20one%20ever%20held%20a%20leadership%20position%20or%20achieved%20some%20degree%20of%20coercive%20power%20over%20others%3B%20however%2C%20to%20the%20extent%20that%20leadership%20or%20coercive%20power%20was%20institutionalised%2C%20it%20remained%20impermanent%2C%20limited%2C%20and%20contingent.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20377px)%2085vw%2C%20377px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22377%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896.jpg%20874w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-219x300.jpg%20219w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F11123728%2FIMG_2896-746x1024.jpg%20746w%5C%22%20class%3D%5C%22wp-image-696598%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22518%5C%22%3E%3Cp%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption-text%5C%22%3EIllustration%3A%20Pariplab%20Chakraborty%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20any%20case%2C%20the%20Pleistocene%20climate%20had%20always%20been%20too%20unstable%20for%20hoarding%20to%20become%20entrenched%20as%20an%20economic%20or%20social%20system.%20Before%20the%20Holocene%2C%20conditions%20had%20been%20constantly%20in%20flux%20everywhere%2C%20substantially%20rearranging%20patterns%20of%20rainfall%2C%20plant%20growth%2C%20and%20animal%20migrations%20every%20dozen%20or%20score%20generations.%20But%20it%20would%20eventually%20take%20hundreds%20of%20generations%2C%20living%20in%20stable%2C%20warm%20climatic%20conditions%20for%20societies%20to%20transition%20toward%20systems%20of%20persistent%20socioeconomic%20inequality%3A%20The%20drift%20toward%20full%20dependence%20upon%20surplus%20food%20production%20for%20storage%20and%20later%20consumption%20(%3Cem%3Edelayed-return%20economies%3C%2Fem%3E)%20itself%20took%20thousands%20of%20years.%20And%20after%20that%2C%20the%20ossification%20of%20rigid%20social%20hierarchies%20took%20thousands%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20for%20most%20of%20humanity%E2%80%99s%20time%20on%20Earth%2C%20such%20a%20length%20of%20stable%2C%20temperate%20conditions%2C%20as%20in%20the%20Holocene%2C%20had%20never%20occurred.%20And%20so%20for%20nearly%20all%20of%20human%20experience%2C%20immediate-return%20economies%20and%20fluidly%20egalitarian%20structures%20or%20fluctuating%20hierarchies%20defined%20the%20baseline%20social%20context%20of%20ongoing%20human%20evolution%2C%20as%20human%20knowledge%20systems%2C%20interrelationships%2C%20and%20cultures%20grew%20thicker%20and%20more%20complex.%20Until%20at%20least%20the%20mid-Holocene%2C%20roughly%20five%20thousand%20years%20ago%2C%20all%20human%20societies%20functioned%20primarily%20on%20the%20basis%20of%20mutual%20aid%2C%20grounded%20in%20social%20bonds%20and%20cooperative%20cultural%20norms%2C%20and%20deeply%20connected%20to%20the%20health%20of%20their%20home%20ecosystems.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESomething%20has%20certainly%20changed%20in%20more%20recent%20history.%20Few%20people%20today%20live%20in%20the%20kinds%20of%20balanced%20and%20egalitarian%20societies%20that%20were%20ordinary%20for%2099%20percent%20of%20our%20time%20on%20Earth.%20Instead%2C%20most%20people%20today%20are%20stuck%20within%20the%20deeply%20entrenched%20system%20of%20socioeconomic%20hierarchy%20that%20is%20our%20modern%2C%20industrial%20civilisation.%20This%20same%20global%20system%20has%20largely%20dismantled%20healthy%20ecosystem%20functioning%20across%20large%20portions%20of%20the%20Earth%2C%20rerouting%20the%20flows%20of%20energy%20and%20materials%20away%20from%20benefiting%20ecosystem%20robustness%2C%20but%20instead%20toward%20feeding%20the%20desires%20of%20our%20single%20species.%20There%20are%20now%20so%20many%20humans%20that%20we%E2%80%99re%20literally%20crowding%20out%20other%20forms%20of%20life%2C%20as%20we%20destroy%20their%20habitats%20for%20our%20cities%2C%20farms%2C%20pasturelands%2C%20mines%2C%20dams%2C%20roads%2C%20and%20other%20infrastructures.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ctable%3E%5Cn%3Ctbody%3E%5Cn%3Ctr%3E%5Cn%3Ctd%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBy%2045%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20South%20and%20Southeast%20Asia%20were%20already%20home%20to%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.0810842106%5C%22%3Emost%20of%20the%20world%E2%80%99s%20people%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Around%2035%2C000%20years%20ago%2C%20when%20new%20stone%20toolmaking%20technologies%20jumped%20in%20sophistication%2C%20indigenous%20South%20Asian%20populations%20began%20growing%20even%20faster.%20Perhaps%20this%20surge%20of%20humans%20caused%20the%20local%20megafaunal%20extinctions.%20Further%20innovations%20in%20tool%20technologies%2C%20the%20spread%20of%20cereal%20agriculture%2C%20and%20patriarchy%20have%20each%20played%20a%20role%20in%20rapid%20population%20growth%20at%20various%20times%20since%20then%2C%20such%20that%20South%20Asia%20has%20remained%20among%20the%20most%20populous%20regions%20in%20the%20world.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftd%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftr%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftbody%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ftable%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20human%20enterprise%20now%20claims%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencedirect.com%2Fscience%2Farticle%2Fpii%2FS1439179122000949%5C%22%3E25%25%20of%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20net%20primary%20productivity%3C%2Fa%3E%E2%80%94that%20is%2C%20the%20total%20amount%20of%20the%20sun%E2%80%99s%20energy%20converted%20into%20food%20by%20plants%E2%80%94an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.1211349110%5C%22%3Eamount%20that%E2%80%99s%20doubled%3C%2Fa%3E%20over%20the%20last%20century%20alone.%20And%20since%20sunlight%20falls%20at%20a%20finite%20daily%20rate%2C%20all%20the%20other%20living%20beings%E2%80%94who%20continue%20to%20subsist%20within%20the%20economics%20of%20immediate-return%20energy%20flows%E2%80%94have%20less%20energy%20to%20live%20on.%20We%E2%80%99re%20fundamentally%20changing%20the%20energy%20and%20material%20flows%20of%20our%20biosphere%20in%20a%20way%20that%20results%20in%20a%20%3Cem%3Emassive%3C%2Fem%3E%20increase%20of%20humans%20and%20our%20domesticates%E2%80%94alongside%20a%20commensurate%20diminishment%20of%20%3Cem%3Eall%20other%20life%3C%2Fem%3E.%20In%20fact%2C%20today%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Famp.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2018%2Fmay%2F21%2Fhuman-race-just-001-of-all-life-but-has-destroyed-over-80-of-wild-mammals-study%3FCMP%3Dshare_btn_tw%26__twitter_impression%3Dtrue%5C%22%3Ehumans%20make%20up%2036%25%20by%20weight%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20all%20the%20mammals%20on%20the%20planet%2C%20while%20elephants%2C%20whales%2C%20tigers%2C%20bears%E2%80%94almost%20every%20wild%20animal%20you%20might%20think%20of%E2%80%94are%20fast%20disappearing%2C%20altogether%20accounting%20for%20only%204%20percent%20of%20mammalian%20biomass.%20This%20is%20estimated%20to%20be%20an%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.weforum.org%2Fagenda%2F2021%2F04%2Fmammals-human-agriculture-charts%2F%5C%22%3E85%25%20reduction%20of%20land-dwelling%2C%20wild%20mammalian%20biomass%3C%2Fa%3E%20since%20modern%20humans%20first%20left%20Africa%20and%2C%20given%20the%20decimations%20of%20whaling%2C%20this%20figure%20would%20be%20substantially%20higher%20if%20marine%20mammals%20were%20included.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20so%2C%20during%20the%20same%20span%20of%20time%2C%20the%20%3Cem%3Eoverall%3C%2Fem%3E%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.weforum.org%2Fagenda%2F2021%2F04%2Fmammals-human-agriculture-charts%2F%5C%22%3Emammalian%20biomass%20has%20multiplied%3C%2Fa%3E%20by%20nine%20times%2C%20due%20to%20the%20massive%20expansion%20of%20domesticated%20animals%2C%20especially%20pigs%20and%20cows.%20Today%2C%20birds%20farmed%20for%20human%20consumption%E2%80%94mostly%20chickens%E2%80%94make%20up%20almost%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.1711842115%5C%22%3Ethree%20times%20the%20biomass%20of%20wild%20birds%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Human%20activity%20has%20reduced%20Earth%E2%80%99s%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2020%2Fdec%2F09%2Fhuman-made-materials-now-outweigh-earths-entire-biomass-study%5C%22%3Eplant%20biomass%20by%20half%3C%2Fa%3E%20since%20the%20dawn%20of%20agriculture%20and%20obliterated%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2018%2Foct%2F30%2Fhumanity-wiped-out-animals-since-1970-major-report-finds%5C%22%3E60%20percent%20of%20all%20mammals%2C%20birds%2C%20fish%2C%20and%20reptiles%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20just%20the%C2%A0past%2060%20years.%20And%20the%20rate%20of%20annihilation%20is%20%3Cem%3Eaccelerating%3C%2Fem%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%20class%3D%5C%22wp-caption%5C%22%3E%3Cimg%20sizes%3D%5C%22(max-width%3A%20709px)%2085vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20909px)%2067vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%20984px)%2061vw%2C%20(max-width%3A%201362px)%2045vw%2C%20600px%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113249%2FDecline-of-the-worlds-wild-mammals.png%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%22650%5C%22%20srcset%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113249%2FDecline-of-the-worlds-wild-mammals.png%201200w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewire.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2024%2F02%2F25113249%2FDecline-of-the-worlds-wild-mammals-300x200.png%20300w%2C%20https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.thewir